description: From Middle English lacchen (“to seize, catch, grasp”, verb), from Old English læċċan (“to grasp, take hold of, catch, seize”), from Proto-Germanic *lakjaną, *lakwijaną, *lakkijaną (“to seize”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)leh₂g-, *(s)leh₂gʷ- (“to take, seize”). Cognate with Middle Dutch lakken (“to grasp, catch”).

verbs.description: latch (third-person singular simple present latches, present participle latching, simple past and past participle latched or (obsolete) laught)

entries.meaning: To close or lock as if with a latch.

description: From Middle English latche, lacche (“a latch; a trap”), from lacchen (“to seize, catch, grasp”), from Old English læċċan (“to grasp, take hold of, catch, seize”). See above for more.

entries.meaning: A fastening for a door that has a bar that fits into a notch or slot, and is lifted by a lever or string from either side.
(electronics) An electronic circuit that is like a flip-flop, except that it is level triggered instead of edge triggered.
(obsolete) That which fastens or holds; a lace; a snare.
A breastfeeding baby's connection to the breast.
(databases) A lightweight lock to protect internal structures from being modified by multiple concurrent accesses.
